abstract: Twelve Democratic candidates for president gathered in Ohio for the debate hosted by CNN and The New York Times. Here were the highlights from the night.
snippet: Twelve Democratic candidates for president gathered in Ohio for the debate hosted by CNN and The New York Times. Here were the highlights from the night.
lead_paragraph: Tuesday’s CNN/New York Times debate in Ohio featured 12 candidates: Joe Biden, Elizabeth Warren, Bernie Sanders, Kamala Harris, Pete Buttigieg, Cory Booker, Amy Klobuchar, Andrew Yang, Beto O’Rourke, Julián Castro, Tulsi Gabbard and Tom Steyer.

abstract: Twelve Democratic presidential candidates shared the stage in Ohio for the fourth televised primary debate.
snippet: Twelve Democratic presidential candidates shared the stage in Ohio for the fourth televised primary debate.
lead_paragraph: It was an unusual juxtaposition for Democrats — calling a Republican president weak militarily.

abstract: The criticism of Elizabeth Warren illustrated her status as an emerging front-runner, while Joe Biden faced scrutiny over his son’s financial dealings overseas.
snippet: The criticism of Elizabeth Warren illustrated her status as an emerging front-runner, while Joe Biden faced scrutiny over his son’s financial dealings overseas.
lead_paragraph: WESTERVILLE, Ohio — Senator Elizabeth Warren of Massachusetts faced a sustained barrage of criticism from her Democratic rivals at a presidential debate in Ohio on Tuesday, tangling with a group of underdog moderates who assailed her liberal economic proposals, while former Vice President Joseph R. Biden Jr. appeared to fade from the fray after parrying President Trump’s attacks on his family.

snippet: Our reporters followed all of the exchanges and fact-checked the candidates, providing context and explanation on the policy debates.
lead_paragraph: Twelve candidates vying for the 2020 Democratic presidential nomination took the debate stage Tuesday night in Ohio for the fourth round of debates. The showdown — the biggest presidential primary debate in history — was moderated by journalists from The New York Times and CNN.

abstract: Mayor Buttigieg said Senator Warren  had not been forthcoming about whether she would raise taxes on the middle class to help finance a health care plan.
snippet: Mayor Buttigieg said Senator Warren  had not been forthcoming about whether she would raise taxes on the middle class to help finance a health care plan.
lead_paragraph: Pete Buttigieg directly criticized Elizabeth Warren over health care at Tuesday night’s debate, saying that she had not been forthcoming about whether she would raise taxes on the middle class to help finance “Medicare for all.”
